This project aimed to perform theoretical investigations for the development of a highly tunable quantum simulator operated with ultra-cold polar molecules. The main idea was to use rotational dressed states of the molecules as the spin (qubit) degrees of freedom and to  coupled them  by  direct dipolar interactions,  which can be   manipulated and controlled by external dc electric fields  and continuous microwave fields.

Intellectual merit: During this award we investigated quantum magnetic behavior in systems exhibiting long-range interactions such as polar molecules, trapped ions, or atoms with cavity mediated interactions.Specific accomplishments made were:

Proposed the use of reactive two-body collisions to engineer robust entanglement ; 
Proposed to use dipolar interaction to engineer symmetry protected topological phases and Kitaev models; 
Proposed the use of Ramsey spectroscopyto investigate quantum magnetism in polar molecule experiments; In collaboration with the polar molecule group at JILA we observed for the first time dipolar exchange interactions in KRb molecules pinned in a deep 3D optical lattice;
 Developed a cluster expansion and phase space methods for dealing with the non-equilibrium dynamics of spin models with long-range interactions;
 Guided the KRb molecule group at JILA in the effort to suppress losses in a 3D lattice by the continuous quantum Zeno effect; 
Investigated evaporative cooling of reactive polar molecules using dipole-dipole collisions in a 2D geometry;
 Investigated the evolution of quantumcorrelations of Ising models on an arbitrary lattice with decoherence;
 Investigated how to generate spin-orbital coupling and non-trivial chiral quasi-particles using dipolar interactions. 
Performed Monte-Carlo simulations which  helpd the JILA KRb experiment to design a quantum synthesis protocol that allowed them to prepare a low-entropy 3D gas of polar molecules and increase prior filling fraction. The achieved filling fraction of 25% should enable future studies of transport and entanglement propagation in a many-body system with long-range dipolar interactions


Broader Impact: Graduate students and postdocs were trained and involved in the preparation of the research described above. They had the opportunity to closely interact with experiments at JILA/NIST. The PIs disseminated the research by presenting seminars, talks and public lectures
 and by participating in outreach programs. The PIs also wrote accessible review articles.

